name: Language, Learning and Literacy (L3)
aims:
L3 is a whole-class intervention that aims to reduce the
risk of students not achieving expected literacy levels by
the end of their first year of schooling.
description:
L3 is a research-based Kindergarten classroom
intervention, targeting text reading and writing. It provides
rich literacy experiences through systematic and explicit
teaching. It complements the daily literacy program.
Students participate in reading and writing lessons in small
groups, designed to meet their specific learning needs.
They also engage in short periods of independent,
individual or group tasks to practice and consolidate their
current literacy learning. This occurs in the classroom
within the daily literacy session.

name: Unwaste your school habitat
aims: This project achieves its goals in a very effective, low-cost way by organising local communities and contributors doing things large and small. Examples include school children providing the artwork and promotion; local Aboriginal smoking ceremonies and outreach; safe space for larger community engagement and interaction events, such as campus clean-up, workshops and demonstrations. This project enables the community to tackle the largest issue of our time, the environment, at a local level.
description:
Unwaste your school habitat was the idea of Dechen, a nature-loving student at Summer Hill Public School, who asked how her and her friends could have an impact and build a community not just around clean-up but also re-use so that landfills are not the only answer.

Twenty million tonnes of waste find their way into landfill each year in Sydney.  Waste initiatives usually focus on recycling, but reusing, recirculating, and re-purposing objects in addition to recycling is more environmentally sustainable. Children are frequently the decision makers in a family's engagement in extra-curricular activities. This project leverages the change agency potential of children to make "recycle-reclaiming-reuse" a part of the community culture. Further, the reclamation and reuse of found objects promotes a "maker" culture for the children and by extension the community. The community becomes dynamic participants and not a passive recipient of environmental change.

name: Crunch&Sip
aims:
The objectives of Crunch&Sip are to:
- increase awareness of the importance of eating vegetables and fruit and drinking water
- give students, teachers and staff an opportunity to eat vegetables and fruit during an allocated
Crunch&Sip break in the classroom
- encourage students, teachers and staff to drink water throughout the day in the classroom,
during break times and at sports, excursions and camps
- encourage parents to provide students with fruit or vegetables every day
- develop strategies to help students who don't have regular access to fruit and vegetables.
description: Crunch&Sip is a set time during the school day to eat vegetables and fruit and drink water in the classroom. Students bring vegetables or fruit and a bottle of water to school each day for the Crunch&Sip break. Giving students the chance to re-fuel with fruit or vegetables helps to improve physical and mental performance and concentration in the classroom, as well as promoting long term health.

description:

The SALSA program involves four lessons about food choices, physical activity, healthy lifestyle and individual & community action, these lessons are run during regular Year 8 PDHPE classes.
